  "response": "Urdu is primarily associated with the Indian subcontinent, specifically Pakistan and parts of India, but it has complex linguistic origins:\n\nLanguage Family:\n- Urdu belongs to the Indo-Aryan branch of the Indo-European language family\n- Closely related to Hindi, but with significant Persian and Arabic vocabulary influences\n\nScript:\n- Urdu uses a modified Perso-Arabic script (similar to Persian/Arabic scripts)\n- Written from right to left\n\nOrigins:\n- Developed in the Indian subcontinent, not Iran\n- Emerged from interactions between local languages and Persian-speaking Muslim rulers\n- Heavily influenced by Persian language and culture during Mughal period\n\nGeographical Roots:\n- Primarily spoken in Pakistan\n- Widely used in northern India\n- Not an Iranian/Persian language, but strongly influenced by Persian\n\nCultural Context:\n- Associated with Muslim cultural heritage in South Asia\n- Developed as a lingua franca among diverse linguistic groups in the region\n\nSo while Urdu has significant Persian influences in script and vocabulary, it is fundamentally an Indian subcontinent language, not a Persian/Iranian language.",
